<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{sate}}}} is always found at the beginning of a sentence. It indicates that the speaker is going to talk about something different to what has been said up to now.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{sate}}}} can be used when the speaker is going to talk about a new, totally unrelated topic.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@EM{{sate}},@KJ{{in*front^-times}}no@FG{{@KJ{{lecture^righteousness}}:kougi}}no@FG{{@KJ{{continue}}:tsudu}}kidesuga,@FG{{@KJ{{memorize}}:obo}}eteimasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Now, I'm going to continue where we left off in the previous lecture. Do you remember (what we covered before)?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{sate}}}} can be used when the speaker is going to talk about a new topic, but this new topic and the old one are part of the same discourse.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@EM{{sate}},koredeha@KJ{{book^topic}}ni@KJ{{enter}}rimashou.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Now I'm going to talk about the main topic.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{sate}}}} can be used when the speaker is going to talk about the same topic but from a new point of view.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@EM{{sate}},kokode@KJ{{now}}madeo@KJ{{tale}}shishita@KT{{pointo}}wo@FG{{@KJ{{restore^learn}}:fukushuu}}shitemimashou.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Now, let's review the points I have discussed so far.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{sate}}}} can be used when the speaker asks a question after presenting information.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{wa-rudokappu}}@FG{{@KJ{{open^curtain}}:kaimaku}}!@EM{{sate}},@KJ{{now^-times}}hadokoga@FG{{@KJ{{victory}}:ka}}tsudeshouka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
     The World Cup has begun! So which country's going to win this time?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{sate}}}} can be used when the speaker has finished and wishes to announce that he is going to depart.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@EM{{sate}},@KJ{{private}}hasorosoro@FG{{@KJ{{lose^salutation}}:shitsurei}}shimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Well, I should be going now.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{sate}}}} can be used when the speaker is at a loss or thinking about what to do when faced with a new situation.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@EM{{sate}},korekaradoushiyouka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Well, what shall we do now?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

